proof.body:
The derivation proceeds in three steps: establishing the vacuum capacity, defining the dynamic state, and demonstrating the geometric cancellation.

\paragraph{1. The Structural Vacuum Density ($\rho_{\Lambda}$).}
From the \textit{Vacuum Energy Partition Theorem} (Part B), the effective vacuum density is constrained by the global closure condition ($\Omega_{pot}=2/3$) to be exactly two-thirds of the maximal saturation density. This introduces the geometric factor $1/12\pi$:
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\Lambda}(r) = \frac{2}{3}\rho_{\max}(r) = \frac{2}{3}\left(\frac{c^2}{8\pi G r^2}\right) = \frac{c^2}{12\pi G r^2}.
\end{equation}
Note that the factor $1/12\pi$ can be viewed as the spherical capacity ($1/4\pi$) distributed across three spatial dimensions ($1/3$).

\paragraph{2. The Dynamic State ($Q^2$).}
The local intensity of the field is defined by the square of the relational shift vector $Q$. For a gravitationally bound, energy-closed (virial-like equilibrium) system, the closure condition $\kappa^2 \approx 2\beta^2$ implies a dynamic multiplier of 3:
\begin{equation}
Q^2 = \kappa^2 + \beta^2 \approx 2\beta^2 + \beta^2 = 3\beta^2 = 3\frac{V^2}{c^2}.
\end{equation}

\paragraph{3. The Geometric Cancellation (Synthesis).}
The observable vacuum excitation density $\rho_{\text{WILL}}$ is the product of the vacuum capacity and the dynamic state:
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\text{WILL}} = Q^2 \cdot \rho_{\Lambda}.
\end{equation}
Substituting the terms from steps 1 and 2:
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\text{WILL}} = \underbrace{\left( 3 \frac{V^2}{c^2} \right)}_{\text{Dynamic Factor}} \cdot \underbrace{\left( \frac{c^2}{12\pi G r^2} \right)}_{\text{Vacuum Factor}}.
\end{equation}
Here, the Virial factor ($3$) and the Vacuum Geometry factor ($1/12$) exactly cancel to produce the Newtonian geometric factor ($1/4$):
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\text{WILL}} = \frac{3}{12} \left( \frac{V^2}{\pi G r^2} \right) = \frac{1}{4} \left( \frac{V^2}{\pi G r^2} \right) = \frac{V^2}{4\pi G r^2}.
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Conclusion.}
Comparing this result with the standard requirement Eq.~\eqref{eq:newton_halo}, we find an exact identity:
\[
\boxed{ \rho_{\text{WILL}}(r) \equiv \rho_{\text{N}}(r) }
\]
The "Dark Matter" halo is thus identified not as a substance, but as the weight of the vacuum structure itself ($Q^2 \rho_{\Lambda}$).

