Standard cosmological models operate on a descriptive paradigm, fitting dynamical laws (Lagrangians) onto a pre-existing spacetime manifold. We adopt a strictly \textbf{generative} approach based on the foundational principle established in WILL Relational Geometry (Part I):
\href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_I.pdf#pr:unifying}{\[
\boxed{\text{SPACETIME} \equiv \text{ENERGY}}
\]}
\[\text{Throughout this paper, the identity is to be read as an ontological identification,}\]\[\text{not as an algebraic equation or a dynamical law.}\]
This principle asserts that "spacetime" and \href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_I.pdf#def:energy}{"energy"} are not distinct entities but dual projections of a single invariant relational structure. Consequently, we do not postulate a background metric. Instead, geometry emerges solely from the conservation \href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_I.pdf#lem:closure}{requirements} of closed relational carriers.

\subsection{The Energetic Closure Condition}
\hypertarget{eq:closure}{}\label{eq:closure}
For any stable, self-contained system, the energy budget must be partitioned between these carriers. The exchange rate is strictly determined by the ratio of their \href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_I.pdf#lem:dof-indifference}{relational degrees of freedom} ($\text{DOF}_{S^2}/\text{DOF}_{S^1} = 2$). This yields the fundamental \textbf{Closure Condition} governing all bound systems (virial equilibrium):
\href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_I.pdf#thm:Closure}{$$\boxed{\kappa^2 = 2\beta^2}$$}
This geometric identity replaces the Newtonian dynamical postulate. It implies that for any closed system, the gravitational potential energy ($\kappa^2$) must be exactly twice the kinetic energy ($\beta^2$) to maintain topological stability.

\textit{Logic:}
In WILL Relational Geometry, the closure condition of the observable Universe is enforced by the \textbf{SPACETIME $\equiv$ ENERGY} principle. The total relational shift for an energy-closed system is governed by the  \href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_I.pdf#lem:dof-indifference}{form  $Q^2=3\beta^2$.} Since the geometric identity \href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_III.pdf#eq:beta=alpha}{$\alpha \equiv \beta_1$ (derived in WILL RG III)} defines the kinematic projection of the electromagnetic domain, the Relational Limit of the EM-field itself is given by:
\begin{equation}
    Q_{EM}^2 = 3\beta_{EM}^2 = 3\alpha^2
\end{equation}
The normalization of the photon density $\rho_{\gamma}$ relative to the saturation  \href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_I.pdf#sec:density}{density $\rho_{max}$ (derived in WILL RG I)} is determined strictly by this condition:
\begin{equation}
    \rho_{\gamma} = Q_{EM}^{2} \rho_{max}
\end{equation}

\textit{Logic:} Using the WILL RG saturation identity $\rho_{max}(r)=c^2/(8\pi G r^2)$ together with the horizon definition $H_0=c/r$, we obtain the relation:
\begin{equation}
    H_0 = \sqrt{8\pi G \rho_{max}}.
\end{equation}

In \href{https://willrg.com/documents/WILL_RG_I.pdf#sec:precession_law}{WILL RG I (Section 16.5), we derived the universal precession law} for any bound relational system. This law describes the irreducible phase shift (angular defect) accumulated over one orbital cycle due to the system's relational energy density $Q^2$.
\hypertarget{eq:general_precession}{}\label{eq:general_precession}
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{\phi} = \frac{2\pi Q^{2}}{1-e^{2}}
\end{equation}

\textbf{The Expected Calibration Offset:}
The Pantheon+ dataset is calibrated to the SH0ES Cepheid scale ($H_{0,SH0ES} \approx 73.04$ km/s/Mpc). Since our microphysically derived $H_0$ (68.15) differs from this local calibration, we theoretically expect a constant vertical offset in the distance modulus:
\begin{equation}
    \Delta \mu_{expected} = 5 \log_{10} \left( \frac{73.04}{68.15} \right) \approx 0.150 \text{ mag}
\end{equation}
Any deviation beyond this constant offset would indicate a failure of the geometric expansion law ($\Omega$ ratios).

The relationship between the geometric evolution (Phase $o$) and the spatial expansion (Scale factor $a \propto T^{-1}$) is governed by a power law:
\begin{equation}
a(o) \propto o^n \quad \implies \quad T(o) \propto o^{-n}
\end{equation}

The derived exponent $n \approx 0.662$ corresponds to the \textbf{Structural Projection Weight}:
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\Omega_{pot}\equiv \Omega_{\Lambda} = \frac{2}{3}}
\end{equation}
This reveals a Cosmological Scaling Law: The expansion of the spatial scale $a$ is driven by the structural tension of the vacuum ($\Omega_{\Lambda}$).
\begin{equation}
1+z = \left( \frac{o_{max}}{o} \right)^{2/3}
\end{equation}

To verify that the result is not an artifact of axis interdependence:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Null Hypothesis:} A Newtonian universe would yield a horizontal line at $Y \approx 0.707$. The data rises to $Y=1$ solely due to the non-Newtonian boost.
    \item \textbf{Scale Sensitivity:} An incorrect derivation of $H_0$ (and thus $a_{\kappa}$) would shift the curve laterally (Orange Dotted Line), causing a misalignment at $(1,1)$. 
The precise intersection confirms the geometric link between the\textbf{ thermodynamics} of CMB temperature,  the \textbf{Quantum Mechanics} of  Fine Structure Constant $\alpha$ and the galactic dynamics coupling with \textbf{Hubble Horizon} $H_0$.
\end{enumerate}

\item \textbf{The External Horizon Ratio ($\mathcal{R}_{ext}$):} The ratio of the Universal Hubble Horizon ($R_H$) to the particle's Unitary Energy Radius ($r_e$). This describes the particle's \textit{scale} relative to the cosmos.
    \begin{equation}
        \mathcal{R}_{ext} = \frac{R_H}{r_e} = \frac{c/H_0}{\alpha \hbar / m_e c}
    \end{equation}
    \textit{Note: We use the Unitary Energy Radius $r_e$ (Classical Radius) here because it defines the localization scale of the rest energy $E_0$, consistent with the inertial definition of mass.}
\end{enumerate}

