\begin{abstract}
This paper, the third in the WILL series, applies the principles of Relational Geometry to the quantum realm. From the foundational principle \textbf{SPACETIME $\equiv$ ENERGY}, we derive the complete structure of the hydrogen atom. By enforcing geometric and topological closure, we demonstrate that quantization is not a separate postulate but an inevitable consequence of a self-consistent relational system. This framework derives the Bohr radius, the quantized energy levels, and reveals the fine structure constant, $\alpha$, to be nothing more than the kinetic projection parameter, $\beta$, of the electron in its ground state. The derivation requires no classical force analogues, probabilistic wavefunctions, or differential equations, establishing atomic structure as a direct manifestation of relational geometry.
\end{abstract}

\paragraph{Definition.}
The quantized projections obey the same closure relations as their classical analogues:
\[
\boxed{
\kappa_{q}^2 = \frac{R_q}{r_n}
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
\kappa_{q}^2 = 2\beta_{q}^2
}
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $R_q$ is the \textbf{critical quantum radius}, the electromagnetic scale.
    \item $r_n$ is the quantized orbital radius corresponding to the principal winding number $n$.
    \item $\beta_{q}$ represents the kinetic projection of the quantum state.
\end{itemize}

\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=gray!5,colframe=black!80!black,title=Relational Consistency]
\textbf{The same relational law applies at all scales:}\\[2mm]
\[
\boxed{\kappa^2 = 2\beta^2}
\quad\longrightarrow\quad
\boxed{\kappa_{q}^2 = 2\beta_{q}^2}
\]
Quantization is the discretization of geometric closure, not the introduction of a separate quantum postulate. Thus $\alpha$ ceases to be a 'number about electromagnetism' and becomes a geometric ratio defining the phase structure of all closed energy systems.
\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=gray!5, colframe=black!80!black, title=Epistemic Disclaimer]
Equation~\eqref{eq:geometric_uncertainty} is not an approximation or empirical rule. It is a necessary condition for the existence of a well-defined, closed energy projection. Any attempt to interpret $\beta_X$ and $\beta_Y$ as independent classical variables will violate this bound and produce unphysical states.
\end{tcolorbox}

Consequently, the fundamental, irreducible uncertainty in its position, $\Delta x$, is not a limit of measurement but a \textbf{definition of the particle's own geometric scale:}
\begin{equation}
    \Delta x \approx \lambda_n.
    \hypertarget{eq:dx_definition}{}\label{eq:dx_definition}
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Momentum and the Emergence of the Heisenberg Relation.}
The uncertainty in momentum, $\Delta p$, remains the scaled amplitude projection as previously defined:
\begin{equation}
    \Delta p = m_e c\, \Delta\beta_X.
\end{equation}
The de Broglie relation, $p_n = h/\lambda_n$, can be rewritten as $p_n \lambda_n = h$. By combining this with our geometric definition of $\Delta x$ from Eq.~\eqref{eq:dx_definition}, the Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle emerges not as a postulate, but as an algebraic identity:
\begin{equation}
    \boxed{\Delta x \cdot \Delta p \approx \hbar}.
    \hypertarget{eq:heisenberg_emergent}{}\label{eq:heisenberg_emergent}
\end{equation}
This relation is thus shown to be a direct consequence of the particle's ontological status as a self-contained quantum of spacetime. This physical uncertainty is the manifest expression of the underlying Geometric Uncertainty Relation (Eq.~\eqref{eq:geometric_uncertainty}), with the two being linked via the mappings $\Delta p \propto \Delta\beta_X$ and $\Delta x \propto \lambda \propto \Delta\beta_Y$.

\paragraph{Collapse = Phase Locking via Energy Symmetry.}
When the system interacts with an environment (detector, air molecule, thermal photon), the Energy Symmetry Law enforces:
\begin{equation}
    \Delta E_{\text{system} \to \text{env}} + \Delta E_{\text{env} \to \text{system}} = 0.
\end{equation}
This mutual closure requires the system to adopt a \textbf{definite phase configuration} relative to the environment. The winding network locks, eliminating compatibility between multiple paths. Interference vanishes - not because of observation, but because of \textbf{energetic accountability}.

\textbf{Statement:}  
Interference phenomena and coherent superpositions are only permitted in systems that are not energetically bound via interaction with \textbf{ANY} external object or system (including detector or measuring environment). The act of measurement corresponds to a physical interaction that invokes the principle of mutual energy conservation between the system and the detector:
\[
\boxed{
\Delta E_{A \rightarrow C} + \Delta E_{C \rightarrow A} = 0
}
\]

\textbf{Next Steps:}  
To validate the hypothesis, we must:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Test it against canonical quantum experiments (double slit, EPR, delayed choice).
    \item Model systems near the decoherence threshold (partial interaction).
    \item Explore energetic asymmetries between detector and system.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Summary:}
Across all tested regimes, the hypothesis holds:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Coherence exists} when no energetic connection exists between system and environment.
    \item \textbf{Interference disappears} when mutual energy conservation applies due to prior or current interactions.
    \item This behavior scales smoothly: partial interaction leads to partial decoherence, consistent with phase degradation models.
\end{itemize}
